### Learning Order Requirements (CRITICAL)

**CRITICAL**: File numbering MUST reflect logical learning dependencies, not arbitrary ordering.

**Standard System Design Learning Progression** (src/01_introduction/ ‚Üí src/08_failures/):

1. **01_introduction**: Getting started with system design
2. **02_interview-prep**: Interview preparation strategies
3. **03_foundations**: Foundational concepts (abstractions, consistency, failures)
4. **04_principles**: System design principles (availability, scalability, etc.)
5. **05_building-blocks**: Core building blocks (DNS, load balancers, databases, etc.)
6. **06_patterns**: Architectural patterns (caching, rate limiting, CQRS, etc.)
7. **07_case-studies**: End-to-end case studies
8. **08_failures**: Real-world failure analysis

**Why This Order Matters**:

- Foundations (03) must come before principles (04) - learners need basic concepts first
- Principles (04) must come before building blocks (05) - understand principles before implementation
- Building blocks (05) must come before patterns (06) - patterns build upon blocks
- Case studies (07) come after patterns - apply knowledge to real systems
- Failures (08) come last - learn from real-world mistakes

**When Creating New Content**:

- ‚úÖ Verify prerequisites are numbered BEFORE the new content
- ‚úÖ Check that "enables" relationships point to content numbered AFTER
- ‚úÖ Ensure learning dependencies match file numbering order
- ‚ùå NEVER place content that depends on later-numbered files

### File Naming Convention for Split Files

**CRITICAL**: When files are split into multiple parts, use `-part1`, `-part2` pattern (not `Part1-A`, `Part1-B`).

**Current Repository Pattern**:

- ‚úÖ `02_network-abstractions-part1.md`
